%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%
CONTEXT
%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%

THE REGIONAL PROJECT:=C2=A0 DOING project aims to develop methods and too=
ls=20
to first extract information from textual data by structuring it in a=20
database graph, and then to manipulate this knowledge graph in an=20
intelligent way. The envisaged application domain is the health domain,=20
primarily using freely available data (such as clinical cases). DOING=20
aims to design a new form of declarative queries, which can integrate=20
analyses, that will guide health specialists in their decision-making.

DOING (https://www.univ-orleans.fr/lifo/evenements/doing/) is based on a=20
real interdisciplinary collaboration to transform data into information=20
and then into knowledge.

This is a project in the context of DOING@MADICS action and DOING@DIAMS=20
working group.

%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%
SUBJECT
%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%

The postdoctoral research work concerns Task 2 of the DOING (APR-IA)=20
project.

The goal is the development of a first version of a query system on=20
graph databases, whose (declarative) query language would encompass=20
predictive analysis - a term that combines data management, machine=20
learning and optimisation, and which reflects the growing demand for=20
such tools for handling data science problems. The task consists of the=20
following steps:


(1) Modelling a query language on a graph database for the application=20
of a graph node classification method.=C2=A0=C2=A0 There are many applica=
tions in=20
the health domain where the question is to predict the labels of the=20
nodes of a graph (starting with only a fraction of the labelled nodes).=20
For example, predicting whether a patient should be screened for cancer,=20
based on his or her health record, and the similarity of his or her case=20
to other patients. Solutions for node classification using unsupervised=20
methods or convolutional networks exist. The aim is to evaluate their=20
use in the context of databases where only a portion of the graph is=20
available at a time. In particular, we wish to study the problem of=20
prediction by node classification via deep learning techniques. We wish=20
to propose an adaptation of these methods for integration into the=20
Cypher language (Neo4J DBMS).

(2) Method for the construction of query execution plans and study of=20
possible optimisations. The aim here is to prepare the data science=20
pipeline necessary for the preparation of data and the application of=20
learning methods by integrating constraints.

